{"title_page": "Raffles Place MRT station", "text_new": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Infobox station\n | background      = \n | name       = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Raffles Place\n  | zhname = \u83b1\u4f5b\u58eb\u574a\n  | taname = \u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b83\u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bc7\u0bb8\u0bcd\n  | msname = Raffles Place\n  | line = East West\n  | line2 = North South\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code 2I/C|EW|14|NS|26}}\n  | terminicode = \n}} \n | type=[[Rapid transit]]\n | image=File:RafflescityMRTextcopy.jpg\n | image_caption=Station exit of Raffles Place station\n | address=5 Raffles Place<br />Singapore 048618\n | coordinates= {{Coord|1|17|1.97|N|103|51|5.52|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n | line={{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}{{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=North South}}\n | other=Bus, Taxi\n | structure=Underground\n | platform=4 ([[2 island platforms]])\n | depth=\n | levels=2\n | tracks=4\n | parking=Yes (External)\n | bicycle=Yes (External)<br/>No (Inside station)<ref>{{cite web|title=SMRT > Trains > NetworkMap > RafflesPlace|url=https://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/RafflesPlace|website=www.smrt.com.sg|publisher=SMRT|accessdate=7 June 2017|quote=Station Amenities}}</ref>\n | baggage_check=\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | pass_system=\n | opened={{start date and age|df=yes|1987|12|12}}\n | closed=\n | rebuilt=\n | electrified=Yes\n | ADA=Yes\n | code={{SMRT code 2I/C|EW|14|NS|26}}\n | owned=\n | operator= [[SMRT Trains]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (North South and East West Lines)\n | zone=\n | former=Central\n | services={{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|previous=City Hall|next=Tanjong Pagar|notemid=}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=North South|previous=City Hall|next=Marina Bay|type2=Marina South Pier|notemid=}}\n | mpassengers=\n | map_locator={{Superimpose| base = MRT map NSEW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = North South & East West Lines\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Raffles Place MRT station\n | x = 146\n | y = 114\n}}}}\n\n'''Raffles Place MRT station (EW14/NS26)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) interchange station on the [[East West MRT Line|East West Line]] and [[North South MRT Line|North South Line]] in [[Downtown Core]], [[Singapore]]. It is located directly underneath [[Raffles Place]], Singapore's financial district, south of the [[Singapore River]]. Due to its location, it is one of the busiest MRT stations on the MRT network. It is close to several points of attraction such as the [[Raffles Place Park]], [[Merlion Park]], the [[Downtown Core]] and [[The Fullerton Hotel Singapore|the Fullerton Hotel]].\n\nRaffles Place station is one of the five MRT interchange stations in Singapore to feature a [[cross-platform interchange]]; the other stations are [[City Hall MRT station]], [[Tanah Merah MRT station]], [[Jurong East MRT station]], [[Bayfront MRT station]]. It is within walking distances to [[Downtown MRT station]] and [[Telok Ayer MRT station]] on the [[Downtown MRT Line|Downtown Line]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:EW14 Raffles Place Platform C.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform C of Raffles Place.]]\n[[File:NS26 Raffles Place Platform D.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform D of Raffles Place, just opposite Platform C.]]\n[[File:NS26 Raffles Place Platform B.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform B of Raffles Place which is opposite Platform A and on a different level from Platform C and D.]]\n[[Image:Raffles Xchange copy.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Raffles Xchange.]]\nOn 9 October 1983, local ventures had won the MRT job for the construction of the tunnel from City Hall to Raffles Place.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19831009-1.2.45?ST=1&AT=filter&K=Orchard+MRT+STation+construction&KA=Orchard+MRT+STation+construction&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=false&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=&CT=&WC=&YR=1983&QT=orchard,mrt,station,construction&oref=article Local ventures had won MRT job for construction]</ref> On the larger scale, on 4 May 1984, the contractor, Taisei-Shimizu-Marubeni had awarded the contract for the station, Contract 108. To make way for the construction of the station, the Chartered Bank Building was torn down. During the construction, massive rocks were blasted out of the way for the station, which shook several buildings near the station.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shudders from MRT work|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19850521-1.2.19.2?ST=1&AT=filter&K=raffles+place+mrt&KA=raffles+Place+m&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=true&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=straitstimes&CT=ARTICLE&WC=&YR=&QT=raffles,place,mrt&oref=article|publisher=The Straits Times|date=21 May 1985|page=8}}</ref> This station used to be the largest and deepest MRT station in Singapore,<ref>{{cite news|title=Largest MRT station|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19860708-1.2.54.13.1.2?ST=1&AT=filter&K=raffles+place+mrt&KA=raffles+place+mrt&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=true&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=straitstimes&CT=&WC=&YR=&QT=raffles,place,mrt&oref=article|publisher=The Straits Times|date=8 July 1986}}</ref> but the record was broken by [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]] in 2003 and then by [[Bras Basah MRT station|Bras Basah]] in 2010, by [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]] in 2013 and then by [[Bencoolen MRT station|Bencoolen]] in 2017 which is 43 metres below ground. In 1998, some foreigners who could not find accommodation in Singapore were caught staying overnight in the station, and were regarded as loiterers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raffles station becomes Raffles 'hotel' for seven|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19881122-1.2.27.30.1?ST=1&AT=filter&K=raffles+place+mrt&KA=raffles+Place+m&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=true&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=straitstimes&CT=ARTICLE&WC=&YR=&QT=raffles,place,mrt&oref=article|publisher=The Straits Times|date=22 November 1988|page=20}}</ref> It is also one of the four MRT stations to appear in \"Uniquely Singapore Edition\" of the board game ''[[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]]''.\n\nLand reclamation in the Marina Bay area has added more exits to additional buildings since 2000, which is Exit J towards the [[Marina Bay Link Mall]].\n\nThe station is the only MRT station to ever participate in three terrorist exercises, which are Exercise Northstar IV on 11 January 2004, [[Exercise Northstar V]] on 8 January 2006 when it was one of four stations which participated in the exercise on that day, as well as Exercise Northstar VII in 7 July 2009, together with [[Sentosa]], [[VivoCity]], [[Bedok]], [[Tampines]], [[Choa Chu Kang]] and [[Jurong East]].\n\nThe faregates at this station were replaced in 2014. The oldest station entrances A and B were heavily renovated by 28 September 2017 with glass cladding.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nOn 7 October 2017, a small fire was spotted trackside in the tunnel between [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] and this station, but it died out by itself. Its cause is unknown, but it may have been due to a short circuit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Water in the tunnel, trackside fire caused train disruption on NSL: SMRT|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/nsl-disruption-smrt-water-in-the-tunnel-trackside-fire-caused-9289414?view=DEFAULT|publisher=Channel Newsasia|date=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NSL disruption: Train services between Ang Mo Kio and Newton will not be available until earliest Sunday|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/no-train-service-on-north-south-line-from-ang-mo-kio-to-toa-payoh-due-to-track|publisher=The Straits Times|date=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nDue to the ongoing renovation works at Oxley @ Raffles, which is formerly Chevron House, barrier-free accessibility is restricted to Exit D instead.\n\n==Services==\nThis station was opened on 12 December 1987 for the East West Line platforms of the station (Platform A and C),<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19871212-1.2.3|title=Shopping for Xmas the MRT way...|last=Rav|first=Dhaliwal|date=12 December 1987|work=Straits Times|access-date=19 September 2017|via=eResources}}</ref> whereas only the Platform B and D opens on 4 November 1989, when separate operations began for the North South Line to Marina Bay, as well as the East West Line to Pasir Ris.\n\n==Places of Interest==\n* [[Raffles Place Park]]\n* [[Merlion Park]]\n* [[Asian Civilisations Museum]]\n* [[Telok Ayer Market]]\n* [[The Fullerton Hotel Singapore|The Fullerton Hotel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/RafflesPlace.aspx}}\n{{Commons category|Raffles Place MRT Station}}\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|north-south=yes|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raffles Place MRT station}}\n[[Category:Raffles Place]]\n[[Category:Downtown Core (Singapore)]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1987]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Infobox station\n | background      = \n | name       = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Raffles Place\n  | zhname = \u83b1\u4f5b\u58eb\u574a\n  | taname = \u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b83\u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0bc7\u0bb8\u0bcd\n  | msname = Raffles Place\n  | line = East West\n  | line2 = North South\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code 2I/C|EW|14|NS|26}}\n  | terminicode = \n}} \n | type=[[Rapid transit]]\n | image=File:RafflescityMRTextcopy.jpg\n | image_caption=Station exit of Raffles Place station\n | address=5 Raffles Place<br />Singapore 048618\n | coordinates= {{Coord|1|17|1.97|N|103|51|5.52|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n | line={{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}{{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=North South}}\n | other=Bus, Taxi\n | structure=Underground\n | platform=4 ([[2 island platforms]])\n | depth=\n | levels=2\n | tracks=4\n | parking=Yes (External)\n | bicycle=Yes (External)<br/>No (Inside station)<ref>{{cite web|title=SMRT > Trains > NetworkMap > RafflesPlace|url=https://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/RafflesPlace|website=www.smrt.com.sg|publisher=SMRT|accessdate=7 June 2017|quote=Station Amenities}}</ref>\n | baggage_check=\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | pass_system=\n | opened={{start date and age|df=yes|1987|12|12}}\n | closed=\n | rebuilt=\n | electrified=Yes\n | ADA=Yes\n | code={{SMRT code 2I/C|EW|14|NS|26}}\n | owned=\n | operator= [[SMRT Trains]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (North South and East West Lines)\n | zone=\n | former=Central\n | services={{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|previous=City Hall|next=Tanjong Pagar|notemid=}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=North South|previous=City Hall|next=Marina Bay|type2=Marina South Pier|notemid=}}\n | mpassengers=\n | map_locator={{Superimpose| base = MRT map NSEW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = North South & East West Lines\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Raffles Place MRT station\n | x = 146\n | y = 114\n}}}}\n\n'''Raffles Place MRT station (EW14/NS26)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) interchange station on the [[East West MRT Line|East West Line]] and [[North South MRT Line|North South Line]] in [[Downtown Core]], [[Singapore]]. It is located directly underneath [[Raffles Place]], Singapore's financial district, south of the [[Singapore River]]. Due to its location, it is one of the busiest MRT stations on the MRT network. It is close to several points of attraction such as the [[Raffles Place Park]], [[Merlion Park]], the [[Downtown Core]] and [[The Fullerton Hotel Singapore|the Fullerton Hotel]].\n\nRaffles Place station is one of the five MRT interchange stations in Singapore to feature a [[cross-platform interchange]]; the other stations are [[City Hall MRT station]], [[Tanah Merah MRT station]], [[Jurong East MRT station]], [[Bayfront MRT station]]. It is within walking distances to [[Downtown MRT station]] and [[Telok Ayer MRT station]] on the [[Downtown MRT Line|Downtown Line]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:EW14 Raffles Place Platform C.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform C of Raffles Place.]]\n[[File:NS26 Raffles Place Platform D.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform D of Raffles Place, just opposite Platform C.]]\n[[File:NS26 Raffles Place Platform B.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Platform B of Raffles Place which is opposite Platform A and on a different level from Platform C and D.]]\n[[Image:Raffles Xchange copy.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Raffles Xchange.]]\nOn 9 October 1983, local ventures had won the MRT job for the construction of the tunnel from City Hall to Raffles Place.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19831009-1.2.45?ST=1&AT=filter&K=Orchard+MRT+STation+construction&KA=Orchard+MRT+STation+construction&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=false&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=&CT=&WC=&YR=1983&QT=orchard,mrt,station,construction&oref=article Local ventures had won MRT job for construction]</ref> On the larger scale, on 4 May 1984, the contractor, Taisei-Shimizu-Marubeni had awarded the contract for the station, Contract 108. To make way for the construction of the station, the Chartered Bank Building was torn down. During the construction, massive rocks were blasted out of the way for the station, which shook several buildings near the station.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shudders from MRT work|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19850521-1.2.19.2?ST=1&AT=filter&K=raffles+place+mrt&KA=raffles+Place+m&DF=&DT=&Display=0&AO=true&NPT=&L=&CTA=&NID=straitstimes&CT=ARTICLE&WC=&YR=&QT=raffles,place,mrt&